<HEADLINE>
<P>
PARKS, WILDLIFE INITIATIVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * The Times' support of Prop. 180 (editorial, May 15) leaves out one important 
element: the source of the funds to repay the bonds and interest. That money 
will come out of the state general fund, which will be badly out of whack next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
 Those parks and wildlife bonds will cost taxpayers an average of $142 million 
in principal and interest for 25 years. If all the bond measures on the June 
ballot pass, the total obligation will be $422 million a year. And no telling 
what additional bond measures we can expect ahead, for such things as more 
prisons and schools. 
</P>
<P>
 To make things balance, the Legislature will again have to take money away 
from schools and local government. Parks and wildlife are important, but of 
lower priority than our education and safety. 
</P>
<P>
 ALLEN P. McCOMBS 
</P>
<P>
 Chino 
</P>
<P>
 * On a recent trip on Highway 89 to Markleeville, stopping along the curving 
road at Monitor Pass, I looked across the divide over the valley below, 
stretching out like a pale green painting framed in chocolate brown, with 
patches of a giant's snow cone on the mountain peaks. Along the eastern slopes 
of the Sierra Nevada, 7,500 feet elevation, is some of the most beautiful 
scenery in the world, I imagine. The widening sweep of jagged mountain tops 
encircles the blue of Bridgeport Lake. Few who have traveled this route to 
Bodie State Historic Park will forget it, even the washboard road that goes 
with the Bodie experience, a unique view of the 1877 mining "ghost" town kept 
as near as possible in the state of arrested decay, with buildings not restored 
but preserved, down to the last creaking hinge on the dry goods store's door or 
the Miners Union Hall stage curtain. It is imperative that this park, and other 
California state parks benefit from funding provided by Prop. 180 for upkeep 
and maintenance. We must pass this bond issue. We must protect and operate safe 
park and recreation facilities, leading to jobs and more tourism, but also for 
coming generations to appreciate California history. 
</P>
<P>
 JULIA FOSTER 
</P>
