<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: LOS ANGELES; AUTOMATIC 
GAS SHUTOFFS FOR NEW BUILDINGS URGED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Automatic valves that would shut off gas lines in an earthquake should be 
installed in new and remodeled buildings, the head of a key Los Angeles City 
Council panel said Monday.  
</P>
<P>
 Councilman Marvin Braude's recommendation differs from a previous, 
wider-ranging proposal to retrofit industrial and commercial buildings and 
apartment complexes with at least five units.The council rejected that plan two 
weeks ago.  
</P>
<P>
 The Public Safety Committee chairman wants the automatic valve requirement to 
be effective July 1, 1995. The recommendation would cover all renovations 
costing more than $1,000.  
</P>
<P>
 "I'd like to see the ordinance prepared, if that's possible," said Braude, who 
expects the full council to vote on it June 14. "Maybe the Fire Department can 
also help determine those standards."  
</P>
<P>
 The valves cost $250 each, but critics say the devices are plagued by false 
alarms and some did not go off during the Jan. 17 Northridge quake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
