<HEADLINE>
<P>
STANLEY CUP PLAYOFFS / EASTERN CONFERENCE FINALS; DEVILS' NICHOLLS MAKES GOOD 
USE OF ENFORCED REST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Bernie Nicholls' one-game suspension didn't help the New York Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
 Actually, it might have hurt them. 
</P>
<P>
 Nicholls scored two goals for the New Jersey Devils, who moved within a game 
of the Stanley Cup finals with a 4-1 victory over the Rangers on Monday night 
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
 He had missed Saturday night's game after NHL officials ruled his shot at the 
Rangers' Alexei Kovalev had been a premeditated cross-check. The Devils won 
anyway, 4-1. 
</P>
<P>
 The suspension actually helped him. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was my first rest in a couple of months, and I had a lot of jump in my 
legs," Nicholls said Monday. "Regardless of whether I deserved it or not, I did 
get suspended. I felt I let my team down and was excited to get out and play." 
</P>
<P>
 The Devils, with a 3-2 lead in the best-of-seven Eastern Conference final, can 
finish off the series with a victory in Game 6 Wednesday night at the 
Meadowlands. 
</P>
<P>
 The Rangers, whose longest losing streak during the regular season was three 
games en route to the best record in the NHL, lost for the second consecutive 
time in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
 New Jersey, which lost all six regular-season games to the Rangers, took 
control of this one with tough defense and opportunistic offense. 
</P>
<P>
 Nicholls' first goal came in a short-handed situation and his other on a power 
play. 
</P>
<P>
 It was pretty much the Devils' game from start to finish. They held the 
Rangers to 26 shots and not many quality scoring chances. 
</P>
<P>
 "The key is our positional play," New Jersey's Scott Stevens said. "They're a 
team that thrives on other teams running around. 
</P>
<P>
 "We did that in the first few games, but as the series has gone on, we've 
gotten better and better." 
</P>
<P>
 Mike Peluso and Tom Chorske scored the other goals for New Jersey. Goaltender 
Martin Brodeur was within 3:27 of his second playoff shutout before giving up a 
goal to Esa Tikkanen. 
</P>
<P>
 New York's confidence "has taken a hit, no question," Ranger Coach Mike Keenan 
said. "Atthe same time, the Devils have boosted theirs. They've earned that." 
</P>
</TEXT>
