<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: MOSCOW; END OF AN EXILE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Alexander I. Solzhenitsyn, Russia's best known author, is due to end 20 years 
of exile Friday with a flight across the Pacific to the Far Eastern port city 
of Vladivostok, where he will start a cross-country journey to Moscow and a new 
home. 
</P>
<P>
 Solzhenitsyn flew from his homeland in handcuffs with a KGB escort in 1974 
after his writings angered the Soviet regime.Stripped of his Soviet 
citizenship, he and his family lived two years in Geneva and the last 18 years 
in Cavendish, Vt. 
</P>
<P>
 His citizenship was restored in 1990 and Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin 
invited him to return to post-Soviet Russia. But Solzhenitsyn remained in the 
United States to finish writing "The Red Wheel," his epic about Russia on the 
eve of the 1917 Revolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
