<TEXT>
<P>
 BEAR HABITATS: Bears apparently have better things to do than hang out near 
the San Fernando Valley, despite recent examples of the animals wandering into 
suburbia (B1). According to the state Department of Fish and Game, about 60 to 
200 of California's 20,000 bears live in the Angeles National Forest (above). . 
. . In the mid-'80s, the bear census dropped, partly because females had fewer 
cubs. 
</P>
<P>
 JAZZ LEGEND DIES: Renowned jazz guitarist Joe Pass, a longtime Valley 
resident, died of liver cancer at 65. Pass was gifted as a soloist and played 
as an accompanist for Frank Sinatra, Ella Fitzgerald and Sarah Vaughan, among 
others. (A28). 
</P>
<P>
 MONEY TROUBLE: The Pet Rescue Assn. in Sun Valley has spent 15 years finding 
homes for animals nobody wanted anymore. Now, the association is the one that 
needs to be rescued. . . . Because of the quake, many people have priorities 
other than adding pets. "They're thinking of fixing fences, fixing their 
houses," said the association's president (B3). 
</P>
<P>
 WORLD SERIES: Missouri is unranked, and unheralded. No matter. This is the 
College World Series, and no opponent can be overlooked. That's surely to be 
the attitude of the third-ranked Cal State Northridge softball team, which 
squares off Thursday night against Missouri in the first round in Oklahoma 
City. . . . Last year, the Matadors finished fifth in the eight-team 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
 MOVIE MAGIC: Eddie Murphy's "Beverly Hills Cop III" finally opens this week. 
And although the film wasn't shot there, action does take place at a fictional 
Valley theme park -- WonderWorld. . . . But look at a map in the film, and 
you'll see they put the park at the Sepulveda Basin Recreation Area in Encino, 
one of the first places to flood during a big storm. Nice going, Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
 GOING GLOBAL: Lockheed Corp. makes its living in the air, of course. But the 
future of its airport management division is clearly overseas. The Calabasas 
company expects big business as airport development grows in South America, 
Asia and Eastern Europe. See Valley Business, Page 4. Michael Arkush 
</P>
