<HEADLINE>
<P>
DUMP A BAD IDEA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In your article April 29, Moorpark council member Scott Montgomery said he 
found the protracted debate regarding the ill-conceived idea to establish a 
huge garbage dump in Weldon Canyon "a disturbing trend." 
</P>
<P>
 What I find disturbing is that Montgomery, chairman of the Ventura County 
Waste Commission, has endorsed a proposal that would benefit a single 
out-of-county corporation, at the cost of the health and economic well-being of 
the entire county. 
</P>
<P>
 By virtue of the size of this proposed monstrosity, garbage would have to be 
imported from throughout Southern California -- in part to bail out the failed 
projects already installed by the same corporation Montgomery supports. 
</P>
<P>
 And I have news for Montgomery: The garbage won't arrive by helicopter. It 
will travel in thousands of pollution-spewing garbage trucks. It will pass 
through his district and through most cities in Ventura County. In economic 
terms, a dump at Weldon Canyon would harm tourism, destroy the incentive for 
recycling and therefore threaten the tax base. It would make compliance with 
trash reduction laws virtually impossible, increase cancer rates and threaten 
water quality -- all of it solely for the benefit of this shady group of 
investors -- and, Mr. Montgomery hopes, for the advancement of his political 
career. But his divisive political opportunism apparently blinds him to such 
economic nuances. 
</P>
<P>
 CHRIS R. WESTPHAL 
</P>
<P>
 Ojai 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Don't go for the dump initiative. Forget the morality of passing the buck 
because you're scared and opting for a dangerous facility next to working-class 
people you might not like. Sure, it's right up there with cowardice and ethnic 
cleansing, but that's not the issue. 
</P>
<P>
 The issue is practical -- smarts. Interstate Commerce Commission rules won't 
allow any private dump to choose its customers. Are you dumb enough to support 
outside garbage interests and open up Ventura County as a super dump for half 
the state? 
</P>
<P>
 If the garbage industry's initiative passes, Ventura County will quickly 
become the dumping ground for Southern California and, soon after, for any 
county or state that wants to dump beyond its borders. Believe it. 
</P>
<P>
 ROBERT SHIMER 
</P>
<P>
 Ventura 
</P>
</TEXT>
