<HEADLINE>
<P>
GOLF / SOUTHERN SECTION INDIVIDUAL CHAMPIONSHIP; ROYAL'S MARCIANO FINISHES 
SECOND BEHIND WOODS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE ELLING, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Anthony Marciano didn't look like a guy who was all broken up about finishing 
as second banana. 
</P>
<P>
 Truth be told, he was pretty thrilled with the notion, especially since a 
player of considerable repute -- a guy named Tiger Woods -- was the lone player 
to finish in front of him Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's an honor," Marciano said. "I'm an unknown. . . . His round was awesome." 
</P>
<P>
 Marciano, a junior from Royal High, shot a solid one-under-par 70 to finish in 
a tie for second, four shots behind Woods in the Southern Section Individual 
Golf Championships at La Cumbre Country Club. 
</P>
<P>
 Woods, a senior from Anaheim Western High and the two-time defending U.S. 
Junior Amateur champion, shot a sparkling five-under 66, marking the third time 
he has won the section title. 
</P>
<P>
 Woods, who started on the 10th hole, blew away the 130-player field with a 
five-under 30 over the first nine holes. 
</P>
<P>
 Marciano, the Marmonte League champion, shot a two-under 34 on the front nine 
to finish in a three-way tie for second. Marciano earned the second-place 
plaque on the second hole of sudden death by making a 60-footer for birdie. 
</P>
<P>
 The low 22 individuals advanced to the CIF-Southern California Golf Assn. 
Championships June 6 at Redlands Country Club. The only other player from the 
region to qualify for the event was Brandon Jones of Agoura -- and he had to 
work overtime. 
</P>
<P>
 Jones was one of seven players to finish with a 77. Trouble was, there were 
only four SCGA berths left, so seven players teed off in a sudden-death 
shootout for the right to advance. 
</P>
<P>
 Jones sliced his tee shot on the second playoff hole, but punched a seven-iron 
through a stand of towering eucalyptus trees and two-putted for par to advance. 
</P>
<P>
 Ryan O'Neil of Rio Mesa just missed the playoff with a 78. 
</P>
</TEXT>
