<P>
 Boeing Co. Sees Sharp Increase in Orders: The company described a rosy future 
for both airlines and plane makers over the next 20 years and said it expects a 
sharp increase in orders for new narrow-body aircraft over the next six 
years.In its annual market survey, Boeing estimated that at least 2,800 new 
planes that seat between 70 and 170 people will be bought by airlines by 2000. 
Boeing's overall estimate of the long-term growth in the airplane market is 
about 2% lower than its estimate of a year ago, said Richard James, vice 
president of marketing for the Boeing Commercial Airplane Group. Boeing 
estimated that $980 billion in new jetliners will be purchased by airlines 
