<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: CALABASAS; CITY SEEKS TO ANNEX GATED COMMUNITY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KURT PITZER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 At the request of homeowners, the Calabasas City Council has proposed annexing 
a gated community that abuts land slated for the controversial Ahmanson Ranch 
project. 
</P>
<P>
 Annexing the 825-acre Mountain View Estates would give Calabasas control over 
a larger section of Thousand Oaks Boulevard -- a proposed access to Ahmanson 
Ranch -- but would not block plans for the mini-city, said Calabasas Planning 
Director Steve Harris. 
</P>
<P>
 Calabasas must get permission to annex the land from the Los Angeles County 
Local Agency Formation Commission, which oversees boundary changes. 
</P>
<P>
 Calabasas sent its application to the commission this month, Harris said, but 
the review process often takes as long as a year.  
</P>
<P>
 The application was filed after 49 residents of the area north of the Ventura 
Freeway between the city line and Crummer Canyon Road petitioned Calabasas 
officials, saying they wanted to enjoy the benefits of living in the city. The 
area includes Gates Canyon Park. 
</P>
<P>
 "We think Calabasas is going to be one of the most culturally oriented cities 
as it grows," said Bill Bell, vice president of Mountain View Estates 
Homeowners Assn. 
</P>
<P>
 "We want to be able to use the recreation facilities and the opportunities for 
getting together with our neighbors." 
</P>
<P>
 "When we moved in," Bell said. "most of us thought we were part of Calabasas." 
KURT PITZER 
</P>
</TEXT>
