<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VALLEY FOCUS: STUDIO CITY; TEMPORARY STREET CLOSURE TIES TRAFFIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KAY HWANGBO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Residents are complaining about traffic congestion caused by the temporary 
closure of Universal Place between Lankershim Boulevard and Willowcrest Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
 Homeowners who live in the Weddington Park South neighborhood say that the 
closure, due to water pipe replacement under Universal Place, has made 
Bluffside and Valley Heart drives the only routes into and out of their 
neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
 Before April 11, when the project began, neighbors could also use Universal 
Place for access to Lankershim Boulevard. 
</P>
<P>
 The problem, neighbors say, is motorists on Lankershim who block the 
intersection with Valley Heart Drive, making it difficult for residents to use 
the only entrance and exit route currently available to them. The 
pipe-replacement project is scheduled to be completed by the end of this month. 
</P>
<P>
 Biff Elliot, a resident of Weddington Park South, said that he has had to wait 
up to 15 minutes to turn onto Lankershim.  
</P>
<P>
 "I can't go out of here," said neighbor Dee Crider. "A couple of mornings ago, 
at 10:30, I had to wait for three lights because traffic (on Lankershim) looked 
like a slow-moving parking lot." 
</P>
<P>
 Elliot and Crider said they would like to see the city or county assign a 
traffic officer to the corner to stop drivers from blocking the intersection. 
Elliot said the problem is worse on nights when there are special events at the 
Universal Amphitheatre. 
</P>
<P>
 A traffic officer or supervisor will be sent to check on that intersection 
Friday and Saturday, said Betty McMaryion, a senior supervisor with the Los 
Angeles Department of Transportation's Valley Parking Enforcement Office, which 
is responsible for directing traffic in emergencies and other unusual 
circumstances.  
</P>
<P>
 But McMaryion said that, due to a shortage of traffic officers, someone cannot 
be assigned to that intersection on a regular basis and will only return when 
her office receives a complaint. The traffic supervisor said she was not aware 
of the Department of Water and Power, which is replacing the pipe, requesting 
traffic assistance related to the project. KAY HWANGBO 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA052494-0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 044909 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
May 24, 1994, Tuesday, Valley Edition 
</P>
