<HEADLINE>
<P>
SANTA CLARITA / ANTELOPE VALLEY; SUSPECTED RACIST IN PLEA BARGAIN FOR ROAD 
VIOLATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARK SABBATINI, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A suspected white supremacist ended a controversial legal battle over his 
arrest for a minor driving offense by agreeing to a plea bargain Monday under 
which he was sentenced to 35 days in County Jail. 
</P>
<P>
 Jace Edwards, 18, of Canyon Country, pleaded guilty in Newhall Municipal Court 
to driving with a suspended license in May, said Deputy Dist. Atty. Dan Damon. 
Edwards, who committed the same offense in March, pleaded guilty to violating 
his probation, Damon said. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition to the jail term, Edwards was ordered to perform 17 days of 
community service and serve two years of probation. 
</P>
<P>
 Deputy Public Defender James Racusin said Edwards consented to the plea 
bargain because he might have served more time in jail waiting for the case to 
go to trial than he will under the jail term agreed upon. 
</P>
<P>
 Edwards was arrested May 17 when Los Angeles County sheriff's deputies spotted 
him driving near Canyon High School and found three knives in his car. 
Informants told deputies Edwards was part of a "white power" group that helped 
incite two racially motivated brawls involving 20 to 30 youths near the school 
May 10, although he did not take part in the fights. 
</P>
<P>
 Racusin said Edwards joined the group for companionship, but dropped out about 
three weeks before the disputes. 
</P>
<P>
 The district attorney's office and Edwards' lawyer had disputed his bail, 
which was originally set at $500,000. Edwards' parents and lawyer complained 
the bail was excessively high and maintained prosecutors were trying to hold 
Edwards to build a case implicating him in the brawl. Deputies argued the bail 
was sufficient because he was a flight risk and was on probation. In addition, 
he had claimed to have $600,000 from a court settlement that would enable him 
to make a high bail. 
</P>
<P>
 No charges were filed against Edwards for possessing the knives. His bail had 
been reduced Thursday to $100,000, which his parents and attorney also 
maintained was too high. 
</P>
</TEXT>
